---
title: "Why Every Operations Team Needs a Crisis Response Tied to an Audit Log"
date: "2024-10-22"
summary: "Tie crisis response to an audit log. When something breaks, the log tells you what happened, who did it, and what changed."
coverImage: ""
tags:
  - "Operations"
author: "Redevise"
---

When a critical business system goes down and your team is left scrambling to diagnose the cause without a record of what changed, who authorized it, or when it occurred, the diagnostic process grinds to a halt.

A system outage is not the time to realize you need a searchable audit trail; rather, the inevitability of a crisis is the primary reason you build one from day one.

An audit log tied to crisis response means every action is logged. Every change. Every access. Every configuration update. When something breaks, the log tells the story.

Implementing this structure effectively requires a systematic, three-step methodology:

Log every mutation. Every create, update, delete. The user. The timestamp. The old value. The new value.

Log every access. Who viewed what. When. From where.

Log every configuration change. Every setting. Every threshold. Every rule.

Tie the log to the crisis response. When a crisis occurs, the first step is to check the log. What changed in the last 24 hours. Who changed it. What was the previous state.

In our client engagements at Redevise, we regularly design and deploy these solutions. For example, when partnering with a fast-growing team in 2024, we investigated a crisis. Their system went down at 2 AM. The audit log showed a configuration change at 11 PM the previous night. The change was made by a contractor. The change was incorrect. The system was restored in 30 minutes. Without the log, the investigation would have taken days.

The teams that build audit logs are the ones that resolve crises in minutes. The teams that do not are the ones that resolve crises in days.

Log every mutation. Log every access. Log every change. Tie it to the crisis response. The log is not optional.
